   How To File A Complaint

   The FCC does not regulate the Internet or Internet Service Providers
   (ISPs.) You may contact your state consumer protection office or, if
   there is possible fraud involved, you may contact the Federal Trade
   Commission.
     * Procedures For Filing a Complaint
     * Frequently Asked Questions and complaints regarding issues under
       FCC jurisdiction
     * Consumer Telephone-Related Complaints, including billing disputes,
       cramming, slamming, telemarketing, and taxes
     * Local Telephone Competition & Other Common-Carrier Market
       Violations, both formal and informal, pursuant to Section 208 of
       the Communications Act
     * Broadcast Complaints, including the broadcast of obscene and/or
       indecent material, the broadcast of hoaxes, and broadcast of
       telephone conversation
     * Interference Complaints, including interference with broadcast
       signals, private land mobile service, and Amateur radio signals
     * Amateur Radio Complaints
     * Cable Television Complaints, including signal leakage, indecency
       and obscenity, and Equal Employment Opportunity (EEO) complaints

   Complaints about cable rates or service should be directed to your
   local franchise authority. A franchising authority is the local
   municipal, county or other government organization that regulates
   certain aspects of the cable television industry at the state or local
   level. The name of the franchising authority may be on the front or
   back of your cable bill. If this information is not on your bill,
   contact your cable company or your local town or city hall.

   last reviewed/updated on 12/20/01
